[[File:Abraham Manievich. Self-Portrait.jpg|thumb|Self-Portrait (1924)]][[File:Artist's Wife.jpg|thumb| Artist's Wife (1937) ]] {{Use mdy dates|date=April 2016}}
'''Abraham A. Manievich (Abram Manevich)''' (1881 [[Mstsislaw]], [[Belorus|Belarus]] – 1942 [[Bronx]], [[United States]]) was a Ukrainian-American Jewish expressionist artist.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,730014,00.html|title=Art: Queer Manievich – TIME|date=February 14, 1927}}</ref><ref>https://www.wikiart.org/en/abraham-manievich</ref>
==Life== He studied art at the Kiev Art School from 1901 to 1905, and at the Academy of Art in Munich, Germany.<ref>http://archive.jta.org/1942/07/01/archive/abraham-manievich-prominent-jewish-painter-dies-in-new-york</ref> After travelling and successfully exhibiting in Italy, France,and Switzerland<ref>http://www.sothebys.com/en/auctions/ecatalogue/2012/important-russian-art/lot.19.lotnum.html</ref> as well as Kiev, he lived in Moscow from 1916 to 1917.
A co-founder of the Ukrainian Academy of Arts,<ref>[[:File:Founders of the Ukrainian academy of arts.jpg]]</ref> he taught at the [[Modern Art Research Institute of Ukrainian Academy of Arts|Ukrainian Academy of Fine Arts]]. In 1921, Following the death of his son in the pogrom-initiated destruction of the Kiev ghetto,<ref>http://thejewishmuseum.org/collection/3474-destruction-of-the-ghetto-kiev</ref> he immigrated to the United States.<ref>[http://www.zoryafineart.com/artists/13/abram-manevich Abram Manevich on Zorya Fine Art]</ref> His continued work enjoyed critical acclaim until his death.<ref>http://thejewishmuseum.org/collection/3474-destruction-of-the-ghetto-kiev</ref>
His work is in the [[National Art Museum of Ukraine]] and in major museums and private collections in the United States, Canada, France, Israel, Russia, and Ukraine.<ref>[http://www.zoryafineart.com/artists/13/abram-manevich Abram Manevich on Zorya Fine Art]</ref> His papers are held at the [[Archives of American Art]].<ref>[http://www.aaa.si.edu/collections/abraham-manievich-papers-13487 Summary of the Abraham Manievich papers, 1883–1973, (bulk 1883–1942) | Archives of American Art, Smithsonian Institution]</ref>
